Preventing SQL Injection in Shiny Applications

Matthew Sharkey

March 15, 2019

R Markdown

The Open Web Application Security Project (OWASP) ranks injection based attacks as the number one security risk to web applications.

OWASP - Not for profit,Technology Agnostic, Contributed to by Security Community. OWASP is widley considered a standard for measuring security in web applications.

Why is injection at the top? It’s extremely easy to exploit, automated tools, basic SQL knowledge. It’s still prevelent today, as long as companies dynamic code this risk will not disappear. The impact to organizations is severe.

The number one risk on the web today is injections(get source for this). If using a relational database that introduces the risk for SQL injection risk specifically. It’s very easy to exploit SQL injections. Sony had a massive data breach that at the root was a sql injection. (add source).

Defense techniques: White list known inputs,don’t be to restrive of the characterset. Some characters are legit e.g. Lee’s Summit. Don’t use a blacklist, it’s hard to predict what will be

Query Parameterization. Seperate the data from being able to being able to manipulate query logic.

  • Query can’t be changed at run time.

Stored Procedure defense

Server Side Defense -Principle of least privelage,only grant execute to stored procs.

Network Isolation, Only alow connections through the web app.

Use IDS, Intrustion Dection System, WAF like baricuda, CloudFlare

Keep Database and Webservers patched.

-Hash and Salt Sensitve Values, If you never need to reference the source system directly why do you need to maintain the original values? For example passwords. store passwords in plain text.

–Limit Account Web Account privelages
